                </a></li></ul></div><p><strong>Figure 7.  <span>A model of hypotonic-induced Ca<sup>2+</sup> transients in Merkel cells.</span></strong></p><a id="article1.body1.sec4.fig1.caption1.p1" name="article1.body1.sec4.fig1.caption1.p1"></a><p>Hypotonic solutions stimulate water influx across the cell membrane, causing cell swelling. The increased tension on the membrane activates Ca<sup>2+</sup> permeable channels. These channels both contribute to a rise in Ca<sup>2+</sup> influx and depolarize the membrane, opening VACCs. VACCs and Ca<sup>2+</sup> release from internal stores amplify Ca<sup>2+</sup> signals.</p>
